n of a child. While most policies are designed to help women return to work, this is only half of the puzzle. The second half requires men to be meaningful partners by encouraging them to take equal time at home.Ultimately, Kaufman arrives at a rational solution that will promote gender equity through a policy that enables parents at companies of all sizes to spend six months with their new child.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh  aBreastfeeding.  aChildren’s health.  aDaddy "a.  aEmployer policies.  aEqual parenting.  aFamily and Medical Leave Act.  aFathers and caregiving.  aGay couples.  aGender equality.  aGendered policies.  aMaternal bonding.  aMaternal employment.  aMaternity leave.  aMen’s earnings.  aPaternity leave.  aPay gap.  aPostpartum depression.  aSecondary parents.  aShared parental leave.  aSocial policy.  aUnequal pay.  aWomen’s career advancement.  aWomen’s health.  aWorkplace context.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479892990.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479892990423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479892990/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles